{{About|the founding of the medieval Principality of Moldavia|the establishment of the modern Republic of Moldova|Declaration of Independence of Moldova}}
{{Good article}}
{{History of Moldova}}
{{History of Romania}}

The '''founding of Moldavia''' began with the arrival of a [[Vlach]] (Romanian) [[voivode]] (military leader), [[Dragoș]], soon followed by his people from [[Maramureș]] to the region of the [[Moldova River]]. Dragoș established a [[polity]] there as a vassal to the [[Kingdom of Hungary]] in the 1350s. The independence of the [[Principality]] of [[Moldavia]] was gained when [[Bogdan I of Moldavia|Bogdan I]], another Vlach voivode from Maramureş who had fallen out with the Hungarian king, crossed the Carpathians in 1359 and took control of Moldavia, wresting the region from Hungary. It remained a principality until 1859, when it united with [[Wallachia]], initiating the development of the modern [[Romania]]n state.

==Competing cultures in the future region of Moldavia==
Moldavia developed in the lands between the [[Carpathian Mountains]] and the [[Dniester River]], which had been dominated by nomadic [[Turkic peoples]]—the [[Pechenegs]], [[Ouzes]] and [[Cumans]]—from around 900. The neighboring [[Principality of Halych]] and [[Kingdom of Hungary]] started to expand their authority over parts of the territory from around 1150, but the [[Golden Horde]]—a [[Mongols|Mongol]] and later [[Turkic peoples|Turkicized]] [[khanate]]—took control of the lands east of the Carpathians in the 1240s. The Mongols promoted international commerce, and an important trade route developed along the Dniester. The circulation of Hungarian and Bohemian coins shows that there were also close economic contacts between the basin of the Moldova and [[Central Europe]] in the early {{nobr|14th century}}.

In addition to the dominant Turkic population, medieval chronicles and documents mention other peoples who lived between the Carpathians and the Dniester, including the [[Ulichians]] and the [[Tivertsi|Tivercians]] in the {{nobr|9th century}}, and the [[Brodniki]] and the [[Alans]] in the {{nobr|13th century}}. The Vlachs' presence in that territory is well documented from the 1160s. Their local [[Polity|polities]] were first mentioned in the {{nobr|13th century}}: the Mongols defeated the Qara-Ulagh, or Black Vlachs, in 1241, and the Vlachs invaded Halych in the late 1270s.

=== The Vlachs—the earliest Romanians—and their neighbors ===
{{Main article|Origin of the Romanians|Romania in the Early Middle Ages}}
[[File:G 134, Sjonhem.JPG|thumb |right |alt=A rounded stone with an inscripted cross and runes |The 11th-century [[Varangian runestones#Gotland|runestone G134]] referring to "[[Blakumen#Blakumen on runestone G134|Blakumen]]" whom many historians identified as [[Vlachs]] (Sjonhem cemetery, [[Gotland]], Sweden)]]
The Moldavian region—the lands between the [[Eastern Carpathians]] and the [[Dniester River]]—acquired a territorial identify in the {{nobr|14th century}}.{{sfn|Treptow|Popa|1996|p=135}} During the previous millennium, the region had been subject to invasions by nomadic peoples,{{sfn|Treptow|Popa|1996|p=7}} followed by a peaceful period around 750 during the [[Khazar Khaganate]], which led to growth of the population the region.{{sfn|Spinei|2009|pp=48-50}} A new material culture—the "[[Dridu culture]]"—spread in the lands along the Lower Danube (in both present-day Bulgaria and Romania) and in the territory east of the Carpathians.{{sfn|Sălăgean|2005|p=135}} After the arrival of the [[Magyars]] to the [[Pontic steppes]] north of the [[Black Sea]] in the 830s, the local inhabitants fortified their settlements with [[palisade]]s and deep [[moat]]s along the Dniester in the {{nobr|9th century}}.{{sfn|Curta|2006|pp=124, 157, 185}}{{sfn|Spinei|2009|p=85}} [[Ulichians]], [[Tivertsi|Tivercians]]<ref>{{Harvnb| Cross|Sherbowitz-Wetzor| 1953|p=56}}</ref> "Waladj",{{sfn|Spinei|2009|p=82}} and "Blaghā"{{sfn|Spinei|2009|p=83}} are ethnic groups connected with the [[Vlachs]], or Romanians, of the region of the Carpathians.{{sfn|Spinei|2009|p=83}}{{failed verification|date=November 2015}}{{POV statement|date=November 2015}}

[[Victor Spinei]] wrote that a [[runestone]] which was set up around 1050 contains the earliest reference to Romanians living east of the Carpathians.{{sfn|Spinei|2009|p=54}} It refers to ''[[Blakumen]]'' who killed a [[Varangian]] merchant at an unspecified place.{{sfn|Spinei|2009|p=54}}

A competing group, the Magyars, left the Pontic steppes for the [[Carpathian Basin]] after a coalition of the [[Pechenegs]] and the Bulgarians defeated them at the end of the {{nobr|9th century}}.{{sfn|Sălăgean|2005|p=153}}{{sfn|Djuvara|2014|p=52}} The Pechenegs took control of the territory, but most Dridu settlements survived their arrival.{{sfn|Spinei|2009|pp=94, 96}} Only the fortifications were destroyed in the 10th or early {{nobr|11th centuries}}.{{sfn|Curta|2006|p=186}} New settlements appeared along the lower course of the Prut.{{sfn|Curta|2006|p=186}} The local inhabitants' burial rites radically changed: inhumation replaced cremation and no grave goods can be detected after around 1000.{{sfn|Curta|2006|p=186}}

===Mongol invasion and occupation===
According to the Persian historian, [[Rashid-al-Din Hamadani]], a Mongol army "proceeded by way of the Qara-Ulagh, crossing the {{nobr|mountains …}} and defeating the Ulagh peoples"<ref>{{Harvnb|Al-Dīn|Boyle|1971|p=70}}</ref> during the Mongol invasion of 1241.{{sfn|Andreescu|1998|p=78}}{{sfn|Spinei|1986|p=113}} His narrative shows that the "Quara-Ulagh," or Black Vlachs, lived in the [[Eastern Carpathians|Eastern]] or [[Southern Carpathians]].{{sfn|Andreescu|1998|p=78}}{{sfn|Spinei|1986|p=113}} [[Giovanni di Plano Carpini]], a papal envoy to the [[Great Khan]] of the Mongols, met a "Duke Olaha" who "was leaving with"<ref>{{Harvnb|di Plano Carpini|Hildinger|1996|p=119}}</ref> his retinue to the Mongols in 1247.{{sfn|Spinei|1986|p=131}} Victor Spinei, [[Vlad Georgescu]] and other historians identify the duke as a Vlach ruler, because his name is similar to the Hungarian word for Vlach (''oláh''),{{sfn|Georgescu|1991|p=17}}{{sfn|Spinei|1986|p=131}} but the name may have also been a version of [[Oleg]].{{sfn|Sălăgean|2005|p=196}} Friar [[William of Rubruck]], who visited the court of the Great Khan in the 1250s, listed "the Blac",<ref>{{Harvnb|Jackson|2009|p=139}}</ref> or Vlachs, among the peoples who paid tribute to the Mongols, but the Vlachs' territory is uncertain.{{sfn|Sălăgean|2005|p=196}}{{sfn|Spinei|1986|p=131}} Rubruck described "Blakia" as "[[Asen dynasty|Assan's]] territory"<ref>{{Harvnb|Jackson|2009|p=30}}</ref> south of the Lower Danube, showing that he identified it with the northern regions of the second Bulgarian Empire.{{sfn|Vásáry|2005|p=30}}

Archaeological finds—kilns to produce pottery and furnaces to puddle iron ore—identify towns that were important economic centers of the Golden Horde.{{sfn|Spinei|1986|pp=148-149}} At Orheiul Vechi, the ruins of a [[mosque]] and a bath were also excavated.{{sfn|Rădvan|2010|p=521}} The local inhabitants used high quality ceramics (amphorae-like vessels, pitchers, mugs, jars and pots), similar to those found in other parts of the Golden Horde.{{sfn|Spinei|1986|p=150}} The Mongols supported international commerce, which led to the formation of a "Mongol road" from [[Kraków]] along the Dniester.{{sfn|Rădvan|2010|pp=328-329}} Almost 5000 Mongol coins from the first half of the {{nobr|14th century}} have been excavated in the same region.{{sfn|Spinei|1986|p=152}}{{sfn|Sălăgean|2005|p=198}} At the mouth of the Dniester, [[Cetatea Albă]] (now Bilhorod-Dnistrovskyi in Ukraine) developed into an important emporium.{{sfn|Rădvan|2010|pp=476-477}} It was established by [[Republic of Genoa|Genoese]] merchants in the late {{nobr|13th century}}.{{sfn|Rădvan|2010|pp=476-477}}

Weapons and harness pieces from the 13th and {{nobr|14th centuries}} that have been found together with agricultural tools at [[Vatra Moldoviței]], [[Coșna]] and [[Cozănești]] shows the existence of either local elites or armed peasant groups between the Carpathians and the upper courses of the [[Siret River|Siret]].{{sfn|Sălăgean|2005|p=197}}{{sfn|Spinei|1986|pp=162-163, 226}} Hungarian and Bohemian coins were in circulation in the same territory during the first half of the {{nobr|14th century}}.{{sfn|Sălăgean|2005|p=198}} The local inhabitants used pottery of lower quality than those used in the lands directly controlled by the Mongols.{{sfn|Spinei|1986|p=150}}

=== Decline of the Golden Horde ===
The earliest contemporary reference to Romanians in Maramureş was recorded in a royal charter in 1326.{{sfn|Engel|2001|p=270}} In that year, [[Charles I of Hungary]] granted the "land Zurduky" (now [[Strâmtura]] in Romania) in the "district of Maramureş" to a Vlach noble, Stanislau.{{sfn|Carciumaru|2012|pp=173-174}} According to the ''Moldo-Russian Chronicle'', which was preserved in a Russian annals completed in 1505, King Vladislav of Hungary sent envoys to invite the "Old-Romans and the Romanians" to fight against the Mongols and afterwards he rewarded the "Old-Romans" with lands in Maramureş.{{sfn|Spinei|1986|p=197}}{{sfn|Vékony|2000|p=11}} Historians Ionel Cândea and Dumitru Țeicu identify this event with the battle of Hód Lake (1280), Cuman opponents being substituted in the chronicle by tartars.{{sfn|Ţeicu|Cândea|2008|p=280}} Historians Pavel Parasca and Şerban Papacostea identify "King Vladislaus" with [[Ladislaus IV of Hungary]] who reigned between 1270 and 1290.{{sfn|Parasca|2011|p=7}}
With the disintegration of the Golden Horde after the death of [[Öz Beg Khan]] in 1341,{{sfn|Vásáry|2005|p=133}}{{sfn|Spinei|1986|p=127}} both Poland and Hungary started to expand towards the steppe zone in the 1340s.{{sfn|Sedlar|1994|p=24}} [[Casimir III of Poland]] invaded the Principality of Halych already in 1340.{{sfn|Spinei|1986|p=175}} Two 14th-century chronicles—one by [[John of Küküllő]] and the other by an anomymous [[Minorites|Minorite]] friar—say that [[Louis I of Hungary|King Louis I of Hungary]] dispatched [[Andrew Lackfi]], [[Count of the Székelys]], to lead an army of [[Székelys|Székely]] warriors against the Mongols who had made raids in Transylvania.{{sfn|Spinei|1986|p=176}}{{sfn|Vásáry|2005|p=156}} Lackfi and his army inflicted a crushing defeat upon a large Mongol army on 2 February 1345.{{sfn|Spinei|1986|p=176}}{{sfn|Vásáry|2005|p=156}} The Székelys again invaded the "land of the Tatars" in 1346.{{sfn|Spinei|1986|p=176}} According to both chronicles, the Mongols withdrew as far as the Dniester after their defeats.{{sfn|Spinei|1986|p=176}}{{sfn|Vásáry|2005|p=156}} Archaeological research shows that forts were erected at Baia, Siret, [[Piatra Neamț]] and [[Târgu Trotuș]] in the late 1340s.{{sfn|Rădvan|2010|p=334}}

==The founding of Moldavia==
Both Poland and Hungary took advantage of the decline of the Golden Horde by starting a new expansion in the 1340s. After a Hungarian army defeated the Mongols in 1345, new forts were built east of the Carpathians. Royal charters, chronicles and place names show that Hungarian and [[Transylvanian Saxons|Saxon]] colonists settled in the region. Dragoș took possession of the lands along the Moldova with the approval of King Louis I of Hungary, but the Vlachs rebelled against Louis's rule already in the late 1350s. Dragoș was succeeded by his son, [[Sas of Moldavia|Sas]], but Sas' son was expelled from Moldavia by a former voivode of Maramureș, [[Bogdan I of Moldavia|Bogdan]], in the early 1360s. Bogdan, who resisted Louis's attempts to restore Hungarian suzerainty for several years, was the first independent ruler of Moldavia. The earliest Moldavian silver and bronze coins were minted in 1377. The [[Ecumenical Patriarchate of Constantinople]] acknowledged the [[Metropolis of Moldavia and Bukovina|Metropolitan See of Moldavia]], after years of negotiations, in 1401.

The dates on coins found in the area indicate the change of status of Moldavia from Mongolian rule to Vlach rule. The minting of Mongol coins continued in Orheiul Vechi until 1367 or 1368, showing that a "late Tatar state" survived in the southern region between the Prut and the Dniester.{{sfn|Rădvan|2010|p=325}}{{sfn|Sălăgean|2005|p=201}} No Mongol coins minted after 1368 or 1369 have been found in the region of the Dniester, showing that the Mongol rulers did not control the territory any more.{{sfn|Spinei|1986|p=216}} Moldavia initially included a small territory between the Prut and Siret.{{sfn|Sedlar|1994|p=24}} Louis exempted the merchants of "[[Demetrius, Prince of the Tatars]]" from paying taxes in Hungary in exchange for securing the tax exempt status of the merchants of [[Brașov]] in "the country of Lord Demetrius".{{sfn|Sălăgean|2005|p=201}}

===Arrival of Dragoș in Moldavia and his "dismounting" there===
{{Main article|Dragoș}}
[[File:Coat of arms of Moldavia.svg|thumb |alt=A shield depicting the head of an aurochs, surrounded by a star, a crescent and a flower |The [[Coat of arms of Moldavia]], depicting an [[aurochs]], the probable quarry in Dragoș' hunt.]]
[[File:Constantin Lecca - Dragos Voda la vanatoarea zimbrului.jpg|thumb |alt=A bison, which was killed on the banks of a stream, is surrounded by a group of people |''Voivode Dragoș's hunt for the bison'' (by [[Constantin Lecca]])]]

Romanian histories cite Moldavian chronicles, which credit [[Dragoș]], a Vlach ruler, with the founding of Moldavia. According to legend, he led a hunting party to the region and dismounted from his horse at the [[Moldova River]]—whence the name of this event, ''descălecat'' or "dismounting". It was during this hunting trip that he judged the region to be more attractive for his people than the Land of [[Maramureş]] in the Kingdom of Hungary, where they were then living.{{sfn|Treptow|Popa|1996|p=88}}{{sfn|Vásáry|2005|p=157}}{{sfn|Carciumaru|2012|p=172}} One theory by [[Nicolae Iorga]] suggests that the Land of Maramureş was one of the "Romanias" where [[Eastern Romance people|Eastern Romance]] ethnic groups (known as Vlachs in the Middle Ages) had survived the [[Migration Period|Great Migrations]].{{sfn|Andreescu|1998|p=92}} A concurrent theory suggests that the Vlachs of Maramureş came from [[Great Vlachia]] (in present-day [[Republic of Macedonia|Macedonia]]) in the second half of the {{nobr|13th century}}.{{sfn|Vásáry|2005|p=157}}

According to the early 16th-century{{sfn|Spinei|1986|p=197}} ''Moldo-Russian Chronicle'', the Vlachs came to Maramureș during the reign of King Vladislaus of Hungary to fight against the Mongols.{{sfn|Spinei|1986|p=197}}{{sfn|Vékony|2000|p=11}} This document represents Dragoș as one of the Romanians whom "King Vladislav" had granted estates in Maramureş.{{sfn|Brătianu|1980|p=129}}{{sfn|Spinei|1986|p=197}} According to the various versions of the legend of his "dismounting", Dragoș left for a hunting, together with his retainers.{{sfn|Brătianu|1980|p=129}}{{sfn|Spinei|1986|p=197}} While chasing an [[aurochs]] or [[bison]], they reached as far as the Moldova River where they killed the beast.{{sfn|Brătianu|1980|p=129}}{{sfn|Andreescu|1998|p=92}}{{sfn|Brezianu|Spânu|2007|p=127}} They liked the place where they stopped and decided to settle on the banks of the river.{{sfn|Brătianu|1980|p=129}}{{sfn|Andreescu|1998|p=92}} Dragoș went back to Maramureș only to return with all his people "on the fringes of the lands where the Tatars roamed".{{sfn|Brătianu|1980|p=129}}{{sfn|Andreescu|1998|p=92}}<ref name=Bogdan group=Notes>
In the time of King Vladislav, the Tatars led by their prince, Neymet advanced from the waters of the Prut and the Moldova against the {{nobr|Hungarians. …}} King {{nobr|Vladislav …}} sent envoys to the Old-Romans and the Romanians. Thereupon we, Romanians joined forces with the Old-Romans and came to Hungary to help King {{nobr|Vladislav. …}} Before long, the decisive battle was fought between the Hungarian king, Vladislav, and the Tatar prince, Neymet, along the banks of the [[Tisza|Tisa]]. The Old-Romans started the fight, preceding everybody else. They were followed by the masses of the Hungarians and the Romans who were in the Latin faith. Thus the Tatars were defeated first by the Old-Romans, then by the Hungarians and the {{nobr|Romanians.  …}} Vladislav, the Hungarian king rejoiced over the divine assistance. He highly appreciated and rewarded the Old-Romans for their {{nobr|courage. …}} [T]hey asked King Vladislav not to force them to adopt the Latin faith, but to let them keep their own Christian faith according to the Greek rite and to grant them a place to stay. King {{nobr|Vladislav …}} granted them lands in Maramureș between the [[Mureș River|Mureș]] and Tisa at a place called Crij. The Old-Romans gathered and settled there. They married Hungarian women and led them into their own Christian {{nobr|religion. …}} There was a smart and courageous man, Dragoș, among them. One day, he left with his companions for a hunt and they came across the footprints of a bison. Following it, they crossed the snowy mountains and arrived at a wonderful and even place where they spotted the bison. They killed it under a willow and feasted on it. Then God brought the idea to his mind that he should find a new homeland and settle {{nobr|there. …}} [T]hey returned home and spoke of the beauty of that country and of its rivers and springs to the other people so that to convince them to move there. The latter also liked the idea and decided to leave for the place where their companions were staying and to search for a new homeland. It was surrounded by deserted lands and the Tatars and their cattle roamed in the borderlands. Thereupon they asked Vladislav, the Hungarian king, to let them leave, and King Vladislav graciously assented. They left Maramureș, together with all their companions and with their wives and children, to cross the high mountains. Many trees were cut down and many cliffs were pushed aside, but they crossed the mountains and arrived at the place where Dragoș had killed the bison. They liked it and dismounted there. They chose an intelligent man named Dragoș of their number and appointed him to be their lord and voivode, and thus the country of Moldavia was founded by the will of God.
—''Moldo-Russian chronicle'' (Spinei, 1986)</ref>{{sfn|Spinei|1986|p=197}} Ritual huntings which end with the establishment of a state, a town or a people are popular elements of the folklore of various peoples of [[Eurasia]], including the Hungarians and the [[Lithuanians]].{{sfn|Spinei|1986|p=198}}

The "dismounting" by Dragoș took place in 1359, according to most Moldavian chronicles.{{sfn|Spinei|1986|p=200}} Except that the ''Moldo-Polish chronicle'' which gives 1352 as the date.{{sfn|Spinei|1986|p=200}} However, the same chronicles add various years when determining the period between Dragoș's arrival to Moldavia and the first year of the reign of [[Alexander the Good]] in 1400.{{sfn|Spinei|1986|p=200}} For instance, the ''Anonymous Chronicle of Moldavia'' mentioned 44 years, but the ''Moldo-Russian Chronicle'' wrote of 48 years.{{sfn|Spinei|1986|p=200}} Consequently, the date of the dismounting is debated by modern historians.{{sfn|Spinei|1986|p=200}} For instance, Dennis Deletant says that Dragoș came to Moldavia soon after the establishment of the Diocese of Milkovia in 1347.{{sfn|Deletant|1986|p=190}}

Moldavia emerged as a "defensive border province" of the Kingdom of Hungary.{{sfn|Georgescu|1991|p=18}} A version of [[Grigore Ureche]]'s chronicle stated that Dragoș's rule in Moldavia "was like a captaincy", implying that he was a military commander.{{sfn|Carciumaru|2012|pp=179-180}} King Louis I of Hungary mentioned Moldavia as "our Moldavian land".{{sfn|Vásáry|2005|p=157}} The province initially included the northwestern part of the future principality (it is now known as [[Bukovina]]).{{sfn|Spinei|1986|p=203}} In 1360, Louis granted estates to a Vlach lord, Dragoș of Giulești, for subjugating the Moldavian Vlachs who had revolted against Louis.{{sfn|Spinei|1986|p=201}} The identification of Dragoș of Giulești with the first ruler of Moldavia is debated among scholars.{{sfn|Spinei|1986|p=201}}{{sfn|Sălăgean|2005|p=200}}

=== Bogdan the Founder ===
{{Main article|Bogdan I of Moldavia}}
[[Image:Bogdan.I.pictura.jpg|thumb|right|Impression of Bogdan I, the 15th-century founder of Moldavia, by Pierre Auguste Bellet (1865–1924)]]
Most early Moldavian chronicles begin their lists of the rulers of Moldavia with Dragoș and state that he was succeeded by his son, [[Sas of Moldavia|Sas]], who ruled for four years.{{sfn|Spinei|2009|pp=195, 200}} The only exception is the list of the [[Voivode|''voivodes'']], which was recorded in the [[Bistrița Monastery]] in 1407, which starts with "Bogdan Voivode".{{sfn|Andreescu|1998|p=94}} Bogdan, who had been the voivode of the Vlachs in Maramureș, gathered the Vlachs in that district and "secretly passed into Moldavia", according to John of Küküllő's chronicle.{{sfn|Spinei|1986|p=206}}{{sfn|Vásáry|2005|p=159}} Royal charters recorded that Bogdan had come into a conflict with János Kölcsei, the royal [[castellan]] of [[Vyshkovo|Visk]] (now Vyshkovo in Ukraine), in 1343, and with a Vlach lord in Maramureș, Giula of Giulești, in 1349.{{sfn|Carciumaru|2012|p=182}} According to historian Radu Carciumaru, Bogdan's conflict with the royal castellan suggests that he had been opposed to the presence of the representatives of royal authority in Maramureș years before he left for Moldavia.{{sfn|Carciumaru|2012|p=182}}

The dating of Bogdan's departure from Maramureș is uncertain.{{sfn|Carciumaru|2012|pp=183-184}} His estates there were confiscated and granted to the son of Sas, [[Balc of Moldavia|Balc]], according to a royal diploma, issued on 2 February 1365.{{sfn|Vásáry|2005|p=159}}{{sfn|Spinei|2009|p=207}} Consequently, Bogdan must have come to Moldavia before that date.{{sfn|Spinei|2009|pp=207-208}} Historian Pál Engel dates Bogdan's arrival as 1359, taking advantage of the power vacuum that followed the death of [[Berdi Beg]], Khan of the Golden Horde.{{sfn|Engel|2001|p=166}} According to Carciumaru, a lasting conflict between King Louis I of Hungary and [[Charles IV, Holy Roman Emperor]] and the Lithuanians' victory over the Tatars in the [[Battle of Blue Waters]] in the early 1360s, enabled Bogdan to come to Moldavia and expel Balc in 1363.{{sfn|Carciumaru|2012|p=184}} Sălăgean says that it was only in 1365 that Bogdan seized power in Moldavia with the assistance of local Vlachs.{{sfn|Sălăgean|2005|p=135}}

King Louis I of Hungary attempted to restore his rule in Moldavia, but the chronology of the military actions against Bogdan is uncertain.{{sfn|Engel|2001|p=166}}{{sfn|Deletant|1986|p=191}} John of Küküllő wrote that Bogdan "was often battled against" by the army of Louis, but the "number of Vlachs inhabiting that land increased, transforming it into a country".{{sfn|Spinei|1986|p=207}}{{sfn|Sălăgean|2005|p=201}} Although Küküllő stated that Bogdan was finally forced to accept Louis's suzerainty and to pay a yearly tribute to him, modern historians{{spaced ndash}}including Denis Deletant, Tudor Sălăgean, Victor Spinei, and István Vásáry{{spaced ndash}}agree that Bogdan could actually preserve the independence of Moldavia.{{sfn|Vásáry|2005|p=159}}{{sfn|Deletant|1986|p=191}}{{sfn|Sălăgean|2005|p=135}}{{sfn|Spinei|2009|p=211}}

===Successors to Bogdan===
{{Main article|Romania in the Middle Ages}}
[[File:Moldova 1483 EnglishPNG.png|right|thumb|The Principality of Moldavia at its peak in 1483]]

The new state derived its name from the Moldova River.{{sfn|Vásáry|2005|p=143}} In Latin and Slavic documents, it was mentioned as "Moldova", "Moldava" or "Moldavia".{{sfn|Vásáry|2005|p=143}} On the other hand, the Byzantines, who regarded it as a new [[Vlachia]], referred to the country as Maurovlachia ("Black Vlachia"), Rusovlachia ("Vlachia near Russia") or Moldovlachia ("Moldavian Vlachia").{{sfn|Vásáry|2005|p=143}} The Turkish name of Moldavia{{spaced ndash}}Kara Boğdan{{spaced ndash}}demonstrates Bogdan's preeminent role in the establishment of the principality.{{sfn|Vásáry|2005|p=160}}

====Lațcu====
Bogdan was succeeded by his son, Lațcu, around 1367.{{sfn|Sălăgean|2005|p=201}} After Franciscan friars from Poland converted him to Catholicism, Lațcu initiated the establishment of a Roman Catholic diocese in Moldavia in 1370.{{sfn|Dobre|2009|p=39}}{{sfn|Deletant|1986|p=193}} His direct correspondence with the [[Holy See]] shows that he wanted to demonstrate the independence of Moldavia.{{sfn|Deletant|1986|p=193}} Upon Lațcu's request, [[Pope Gregory XI]] set up the [[Roman Catholic Diocese]] of [[Siret]] in 1371, addressing his bull to "Lațcu, Duke of Moldavia".{{sfn|Sălăgean|2005|p=201}}{{sfn|Andreescu|1998|p=95}} According to Sălăgean, the Holy See "consolidated the international status of Moldavia" by granting the title "duke" to Lațcu.{{sfn|Sălăgean|2005|p=201}} On 14 March 1372, King Louis I of Hungary, who had also inherited Poland in 1370, signed a treaty with Emperor Charles IV who acknowledged Louis's rights in many lands, including Moldavia.{{sfn|Deletant|1986|pp=194-195}}

====Petru II Muşat====
Lațcu, who died in 1375, was succeeded by [[Petru II of Moldavia|Petru II Muşat]], according to the earliest lists of the rulers of Moldavia.{{sfn|Spinei|1986|pp=195, 217}} However, the 15th-century ''Lithuanian-Ruthenian Chronicle'' wrote that the Vlachs elected [[George Koriatovich]]—who was a nephew of [[Algirdas]], [[Grand Prince of Lithuania]], and ruled in [[Podolia]] under Polish suzerainty{{sfn|Andreescu|1998|p=96}}—to be voivode, but later poisoned him.{{sfn|Spinei|1986|p=217}}{{sfn|Deletant|1986|p=198}} In late 1377, [[Vladislaus II of Opole]], who administered Halych in the name of King Louis I of Hungary, gave shelter to one "Vlach voivode", named George, who had fled to Halych because of the "unexpected treason of his people".{{sfn|Spinei|1986|p=217}}{{sfn|Andreescu|1998|p=96}}  According to Spinei, George Koriatovich died in 1375, which excluds his identification with "Voivode George".{{sfn|Spinei|1986|p=217}} Spinei also says that George Koriatovich most probably ruled in southeastern Moldavia which had been liberated from Mongol rule.{{sfn|Spinei|1986|p=217}} The first Moldavian silver and bronze coins were minted for Petru II Muşat in 1377.{{sfn|Georgescu|1991|p=27}}

According to a record in the register of the Genoese colony in [[Caffa]] on the Black See, two Genoese envoys were sent to "Constantino et Petro vayvoda" in 1386.{{sfn|Vásáry|2005|pp=164-165}}{{sfn|Spinei|1986|p=218}} Historians identified Voivode Constantino with [[Costea of Moldavia|Costea]], whom the list of the voivodes of Moldavia, recorded in the [[Bistrița Monastery]], mentioned between Lațcu and Peter.{{sfn|Spinei|1986|p=218}} The record in the Caffa register suggests that the two voivodes—Costea and Petru II Muşat—had the same position.{{sfn|Spinei|1986|p=218}} The division of the medieval principality into two greater administrative units—''Ţara de Sus'' ("Upper Country") and ''Ţara de Jos'' ("Lower Country")—each administered by a high official, the ''[[vornic]]'', also implies the former existence of two polities, which were united by the Moldavian monarchs.{{sfn|Spinei|1986|p=220}}{{sfn|Brezianu|Spânu|2007|pp=382-383}}

Petru II Muşat paid homage to [[Władysław II Jagiełło]], [[King of Poland]], in Kraków on 26 September 1387.{{sfn|Deletant|1986|p=191}} Upon Peter's request, Anton, the Orthodox [[Metropolis of Halych|Metropolitan of Halych]], ordained two bishops for Moldova, one of them being Joseph Mușat, who was related to the voivode.{{sfn|Papadakis|Meyendorff|1994|p=264}} However, the [[Ecumenical Patriarch of Constantinople]] refused to acknowledge their consecration.{{sfn|Papadakis|Meyendorff|1994|p=264}} Petru II Muşat expanded his authority as far as the Danube and the Black Sea.{{sfn|Treptow|Popa|1996|p=136}} His successor, [[Roman I of Moldavia|Roman I Mușat]], styled himself "[[By the grace of God]] the Almighty, Voivode of Moldavia and her to the entire Vlach country from the mountains to the shores of the sea" on 30 March 1392.{{sfn|Sălăgean|2005|p=202}}{{sfn|Brezianu|Spânu|2007|p=303}} After years of negotiations, the Ecumenical Patriarch, [[Matthew I of Constantinople|Matthew I]], acknowledged Joseph Mușat as Metropolitan of Maurovlachia in 1401.{{sfn|Papadakis|Meyendorff|1994|p=264}}

==Growth of the principality==
{{Main article|Moldavia}}
The Principality of Moldavia, grew to include the territory between the [[Eastern Carpathians]] and the [[Dniester]] river. It existed until 1859, when it united with Wallachia as the basis of the modern Romanian state; at various times, the state included the regions of [[Bessarabia]] (with the [[Budjak]]) and all of [[Bukovina]].  The [[Moldavia (region of Romania)|western]] half of Moldavia is now part of Romania, the eastern side belongs to the [[Moldova|Republic of Moldova]], while the [[Chernivtsi Oblast|northern]] and [[Budjak|southeastern]] parts are territories of Ukraine.{{sfn|Bolovan|Constantiniu|Michelson|Pop|1997|pp=151-155}}

